If we start off with the broader
macro trends as you mentioned,

00:06:05.820 --> 00:06:10.360
you do see a lot of changes
in the political nature

00:06:10.360 --> 00:06:14.590
around the world, and the
forces of globalization

00:06:14.590 --> 00:06:17.290
that were very prominent
over the last 20 years

00:06:17.290 --> 00:06:19.830
as well as capitalism
being really prominent.

00:06:19.830 --> 00:06:21.610
How do you see that
evolving, and what

00:06:21.610 --> 00:06:25.990
role do you think Acumen and
others should be thinking about

00:06:25.990 --> 00:06:27.672
as you think about
capitalism itself?

00:06:27.672 --> 00:06:29.630
JACQUELINE NOVOGRATZ:
Well, as you're speaking,

00:06:29.630 --> 00:06:31.930
you think about how many
governments are actually

00:06:31.930 --> 00:06:33.280
pulling inward?

00:06:33.280 --> 00:06:36.340
Rather than this is a moment
where we need to reach outward,

00:06:36.340 --> 00:06:39.680
which is something that
Google really represents.

00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:42.430
The world I get to see
and Acumen gets to see

00:06:42.430 --> 00:06:46.030
is the next generation that
is looking for new rules

00:06:46.030 --> 00:06:46.540
altogether.

00:06:46.540 --> 00:06:50.710
There's so much faith and trust
lost in the big institution.

00:06:50.710 --> 00:06:55.990
What's so thrilling to me is
to see these entrepreneurs that

00:06:55.990 --> 00:06:59.590
are using more what we
would call moral imagination

00:06:59.590 --> 00:07:00.680
to build new systems.

00:07:00.680 --> 00:07:03.121
So two examples,
one from Colombia,

00:07:03.121 --> 00:07:04.245
one from the United States.

00:07:06.790 --> 00:07:10.690
If you look at coffee
or cocoa for chocolate,

00:07:10.690 --> 00:07:12.310
these are industries
that really were

00:07:12.310 --> 00:07:16.060
born in slavery and colonialism
and the economics of them

00:07:16.060 --> 00:07:17.930
have not changed all
that dramatically.

00:07:17.930 --> 00:07:20.080
If you think about
chocolate alone,

00:07:20.080 --> 00:07:25.360
there are 6 million cocoa
producers in the world,

00:07:25.360 --> 00:07:27.850
90% of whom make under $2 a day.

00:07:27.850 --> 00:07:30.820
On the back of that we're
supporting a $150 billion

00:07:30.820 --> 00:07:32.530
chocolate industry.

00:07:32.530 --> 00:07:34.990
Those economics
really make no sense

00:07:34.990 --> 00:07:37.030
if you're thinking
about the farmers

00:07:37.030 --> 00:07:38.320
that we need to depend on.

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:43.000
And it should be no secret or
surprise that the average cocoa

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:45.310
farmer's 58 years old and
most of their children

00:07:45.310 --> 00:07:47.104
do not want to be farmers.

00:07:47.104 --> 00:07:48.520
On the other hand,
you're starting

00:07:48.520 --> 00:07:52.030
to see an artisinal
chocolate industry take off

00:07:52.030 --> 00:07:55.600
where individual chocolate
bars can sell for $12, $15.

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:58.630
So there's a new
generation of entrepreneurs

00:07:58.630 --> 00:08:02.230
who are completely ignoring
global commodities prices when

00:08:02.230 --> 00:08:03.830
they are negotiating
with farmers.

00:08:03.830 --> 00:08:06.430
They're understanding
the price that farmers--

00:08:06.430 --> 00:08:09.880
or the cost to farmers
of actually producing.

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:12.250
In many cases they're
doubling those costs,

00:08:12.250 --> 00:08:18.460
but providing a margin that is
not 30% better, but 200% better

00:08:18.460 --> 00:08:20.630
than the global
commodities prices.

00:08:20.630 --> 00:08:25.630
So it's left their trade
behind and substituted it

00:08:25.630 --> 00:08:29.020
with a radical transparency
using technology

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:32.679
to show the farmers the whole
value chain from what they're

00:08:32.679 --> 00:08:36.070
paid to what these
chocolate bars are sold for

00:08:36.070 --> 00:08:38.110
to enable communities of trust.

00:08:38.110 --> 00:08:41.770
To me that is so
incredibly hopeful

00:08:41.770 --> 00:08:45.040
when we think about
visibility and transparency

00:08:45.040 --> 00:08:46.900
around the products
that we want to buy,

00:08:46.900 --> 00:08:49.750
and the new generation
cares about that stuff.

00:08:49.750 --> 00:08:52.180
In the United States,
everybody talks

00:08:52.180 --> 00:08:56.230
about workforce development,
certainly in Silicon Valley,

00:08:56.230 --> 00:08:56.860
as we should.

00:09:00.010 --> 00:09:02.110
On the other hand,
we're not doing the job

00:09:02.110 --> 00:09:05.050
that we should be doing in terms
of getting diverse communities

00:09:05.050 --> 00:09:07.540
into coding jobs, for instance.

00:09:07.540 --> 00:09:10.120
We've invested in a company
called Learner's Guild just

00:09:10.120 --> 00:09:13.690
here in San Francisco
that understands

00:09:13.690 --> 00:09:17.530
that low income communities,
particularly of color,

00:09:17.530 --> 00:09:21.670
often have huge stress,
families, jobs that pay

00:09:21.670 --> 00:09:24.100
$15,000, $20,000 a year.

00:09:24.100 --> 00:09:30.070
It's impossible to go to
a good coding boot camp

00:09:30.070 --> 00:09:35.110
and stay in your job and
take care of your family

00:09:35.110 --> 00:09:36.400
so that you can get the job.

00:09:36.400 --> 00:09:39.250
So what these guys have
done is create a system

00:09:39.250 --> 00:09:43.690
where they will give you a
10 month stipend so that you

00:09:43.690 --> 00:09:46.180
can focus fully
on the boot camp,

00:09:46.180 --> 00:09:49.660
at the end of which you have to
pay it back but only once you

00:09:49.660 --> 00:09:51.680
start earning $50,000 a year.

00:09:51.680 --> 00:09:53.260
So there's a risk sharing.

00:09:53.260 --> 00:09:54.760
The first batch
who just graduated,

00:09:54.760 --> 00:09:59.880
the average salary is $81,000
that these guys are getting.

00:09:59.880 --> 00:10:03.010
And they came in at an
average salary of $23,000.

00:10:03.010 --> 00:10:06.630
So we can do this, but it's
not traditional capital

00:10:06.630 --> 00:10:10.680
that will enable that because
there is risk at every level.

00:10:10.680 --> 00:10:12.630
Then Acumen can play a role.

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:16.200
Because what we're focused on
is solving the problem, right?

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:18.810
Not just making money.

00:10:18.810 --> 00:10:21.600
What you learn is that
companies like Google

00:10:21.600 --> 00:10:26.460
and others in Silicon Valley
have requirements for college

00:10:26.460 --> 00:10:28.690
degrees because of h-1 visas.

00:10:28.690 --> 00:10:31.192
So all of this stuff is
interconnected again.

00:10:31.192 --> 00:10:33.400
Many of these communities
don't have college degrees.

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:37.650
So then we can intermediate
and say, wait guys,

00:10:37.650 --> 00:10:40.685
to make this system work
we've got to change that.

00:10:40.685 --> 00:10:42.060
And that's the
way we're starting

00:10:42.060 --> 00:10:46.140
to think about building an
entrepreneurial ecosystem that

00:10:46.140 --> 00:10:48.720
will enable these
companies to change

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:50.790
the way the world tackles
poverty, essentially.

00:10:50.790 --> 00:10:52.470
PRASAD SETTY: Fascinating.

00:10:52.470 --> 00:10:53.910
As you think about
the ecosystem,

00:10:53.910 --> 00:10:56.540
one part of thinking
about these problems,

00:10:56.540 --> 00:11:00.610
thinking about the entire
value chain, as you said,

00:11:00.610 --> 00:11:04.500
then there was a piece
about just the people

00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:08.240
that you're trying to find
and the leadership itself.

00:11:08.240 --> 00:11:11.010
You've been talking a lot
about moral leadership.

00:11:11.010 --> 00:11:14.070
Can you tell us what that
means in your own mind?

00:11:14.070 --> 00:11:15.820
JACQUELINE NOVOGRATZ:
Yeah, and again it's

00:11:15.820 --> 00:11:18.660
this recognition that in
going from an interconnected

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:20.460
to an interdependent
world we will rise

00:11:20.460 --> 00:11:22.170
and we will fall together.

00:11:22.170 --> 00:11:26.430
And that we can no longer
make all of our decisions

00:11:26.430 --> 00:11:28.440
according to a single metric.

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:31.830
And yet it's a lot more
nuanced and complicated

00:11:31.830 --> 00:11:35.490
when you are making decisions
based on multiple metrics,

00:11:35.490 --> 00:11:37.410
based on multiple stakeholders.

00:11:37.410 --> 00:11:39.750
It necessitates
navigating the gray.

00:11:39.750 --> 00:11:42.510
So when we think about the
qualities of a moral leader

00:11:42.510 --> 00:11:45.780
versus just someone
who can get stuff done

00:11:45.780 --> 00:11:48.270
and is focused
simply on efficiency,

00:11:48.270 --> 00:11:51.390
they are individuals
that have what

00:11:51.390 --> 00:11:53.430
we call a moral
imagination, or the ability

00:11:53.430 --> 00:11:57.860
to have the audacity to imagine
the future and what could be,

00:11:57.860 --> 00:12:01.120
but also the humility to
recognize the world as it is.

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:04.410
They are individuals who
see capital, as I said,

00:12:04.410 --> 00:12:07.220
as something that we control
rather than let it control us.

00:12:07.220 --> 00:12:10.042
That see investment as
a means not as an end.

00:12:10.042 --> 00:12:12.000
Something that we don't
think about enough when

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:13.440
we talk about
moral leadership is

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:17.700
grit, resilience,
persistence, courage

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:19.530
to fight the status quo.

00:12:19.530 --> 00:12:22.800
What we've learned is that if
you want to build something new

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:25.140
you are going to be
fighting a system that

00:12:25.140 --> 00:12:27.510
does not want to change.

00:12:27.510 --> 00:12:30.660
And that system is full of
bureaucracy, corruption,

00:12:30.660 --> 00:12:33.190
and probably the worst
of all is complacency.

00:12:33.190 --> 00:12:35.610
So do you have what it takes--

00:12:35.610 --> 00:12:37.110
the determination,
the persistence?

00:12:37.110 --> 00:12:41.190
So we are increasingly looking
for that in every entrepreneur

00:12:41.190 --> 00:12:45.330
that we invest in as well as
the fellows that we're finding.

00:12:45.330 --> 00:12:48.300
Because that will tell
us whether their ideas

00:12:48.300 --> 00:12:51.275
are actually going to take off.

00:12:51.275 --> 00:12:52.650
Probably just like
you at Google,

00:12:52.650 --> 00:12:55.490
we've learned that
great ideas come and go,

00:12:55.490 --> 00:12:58.460
but give us the leader
who have what it takes

00:12:58.460 --> 00:13:00.540
and to do it
ethically in a world

00:13:00.540 --> 00:13:05.550
where so many
systems are broken.

00:13:05.550 --> 00:13:07.470
PRASAD SETTY: What's
been your experience,

00:13:07.470 --> 00:13:11.250
Jacqueline, as you think about
developing this next generation

00:13:11.250 --> 00:13:12.360
of leaders?

00:13:12.360 --> 00:13:15.090
Have you been able to
find them, have you

00:13:15.090 --> 00:13:17.460
been able to scale how
they actually learn,

00:13:17.460 --> 00:13:19.800
and grow, and become
these kinds of role models

00:13:19.800 --> 00:13:21.300
for the rest of the world?

00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:25.040
Any examples, anything from
your experience you can share?

00:13:25.040 --> 00:13:26.370
JACQUELINE NOVOGRATZ: Yeah.

00:13:26.370 --> 00:13:28.470
In addition to investing
in the 100 companies,

00:13:28.470 --> 00:13:33.180
we've invested in about 400
fellows across 32 countries.

00:13:33.180 --> 00:13:40.950
And you know, we've said it
before that talent is is fully

00:13:40.950 --> 00:13:42.390
distributed across the world.

00:13:42.390 --> 00:13:49.470
And daily I am blown
away by the capabilities

00:13:49.470 --> 00:13:56.730
of these individuals who really
need access, capital, networks.

00:13:56.730 --> 00:14:01.200
And so, yes, we're seeing
enormous change happening

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:03.060
at the company
level, whether it's

00:14:03.060 --> 00:14:08.190
someone like [? Gitri ?] who
runs a company called LaborNet

00:14:08.190 --> 00:14:12.030
in India, which a number
of Googlers have helped

00:14:12.030 --> 00:14:13.020
and volunteered for.

00:14:13.020 --> 00:14:15.330
But they've
essentially recognized

00:14:15.330 --> 00:14:20.160
that education in a
traditional school room

00:14:20.160 --> 00:14:23.860
is not going to be the answer
to the world's problems,

00:14:23.860 --> 00:14:27.630
particularly in a country like
India where 85% of the country

00:14:27.630 --> 00:14:29.960
has not gone past 10th grade.

00:14:29.960 --> 00:14:33.230
And so they go into
construction sites,

00:14:33.230 --> 00:14:35.460
work with Muslim
communities doing

00:14:35.460 --> 00:14:38.460
beauty salons, leather tanning.

00:14:38.460 --> 00:14:44.490
And they provide workforce
development training,

00:14:44.490 --> 00:14:47.790
ethical training, safety
training, and then

00:14:47.790 --> 00:14:51.046
cream those who are clear
learners to help them

00:14:51.046 --> 00:14:52.170
get better and better jobs.

00:14:52.170 --> 00:14:54.260
And they've already trained
half a million people.

00:14:54.260 --> 00:14:57.390
So some of these companies
are really working at scale.

00:14:57.390 --> 00:15:02.290
To individuals who are
just getting started,

00:15:02.290 --> 00:15:05.570
[NON-ENGLISH] is
a Pakistani firm.

00:15:05.570 --> 00:15:09.320
Small village in rural Punjab
couple of hours outside

00:15:09.320 --> 00:15:12.530
of Lahore, Pakistan, who
works with local cobblers

00:15:12.530 --> 00:15:17.270
making beautiful shoes
but never had a market.

00:15:17.270 --> 00:15:20.480
He worked with other
fellows across Pakistan

00:15:20.480 --> 00:15:24.770
to redesign his shoes,
rebrand his company,

00:15:24.770 --> 00:15:29.510
now called Markhor, create
a Kickstarter campaign, used

00:15:29.510 --> 00:15:31.430
our network to get
those ideas out

00:15:31.430 --> 00:15:36.680
into the greater world, raised
$115,000 on Kickstarter,

00:15:36.680 --> 00:15:39.080
now is in the Y
Combinator and is

00:15:39.080 --> 00:15:41.480
on his way to building
a company that

00:15:41.480 --> 00:15:47.660
provides good quality visible
jobs to village men and women

00:15:47.660 --> 00:15:51.920
and creates an export
product for Pakistan

00:15:51.920 --> 00:15:54.240
that the country
should be proud of.

00:15:54.240 --> 00:15:58.220
We're seeing this kind
of innovation happening

00:15:58.220 --> 00:16:03.110
in the highest and lowest
communities of India and Saudi

00:16:03.110 --> 00:16:04.400
Arabia--

00:16:04.400 --> 00:16:07.166
across the world, actually.

00:16:07.166 --> 00:16:08.540
PRASAD SETTY: Both
these examples

00:16:08.540 --> 00:16:11.220
show the power of connection.

00:16:11.220 --> 00:16:14.960
How are you thinking
about technology

00:16:14.960 --> 00:16:17.780
as an enabler of these
kinds of connections,

00:16:17.780 --> 00:16:20.552
and what could that possibly
do for us in the future?

00:16:20.552 --> 00:16:22.760
JACQUELINE NOVOGRATZ: Well
one, we get so many emails

00:16:22.760 --> 00:16:25.870
from young people who want to
start companies themselves.

00:16:25.870 --> 00:16:28.970
And two, every time we
launch a fellows program,

00:16:28.970 --> 00:16:33.660
we will get over 1,000
applications for 10, 20 spots.

00:16:33.660 --> 00:16:35.660
So we started to ask
ourselves essentially this,

00:16:35.660 --> 00:16:39.980
could we put the
courses that we're

00:16:39.980 --> 00:16:41.900
training our entrepreneurs
and our fellows

00:16:41.900 --> 00:16:45.230
in, could we put them online,
and would anybody take them?

00:16:45.230 --> 00:16:47.270
And so looked at,
what are the courses

00:16:47.270 --> 00:16:48.440
that people care most about?

00:16:48.440 --> 00:16:52.427
Human centered design,
lean startup, storytelling,

00:16:52.427 --> 00:16:54.260
that you can't really
be an effective leader

00:16:54.260 --> 00:16:55.910
if you can't tell a story.

00:16:55.910 --> 00:17:00.090
And we've now put about
30 courses up online

00:17:00.090 --> 00:17:02.300
and we've seen half
a million sign ups.

00:17:02.300 --> 00:17:05.829
And 300,000 people taking
these six to eight week

00:17:05.829 --> 00:17:08.930
courses where they have to
come together in groups.

00:17:08.930 --> 00:17:11.900
And out of these courses
what's been so thrilling

00:17:11.900 --> 00:17:15.050
is we're seeing
companies being built

00:17:15.050 --> 00:17:17.579
using the same metrics
of moral leadership,

00:17:17.579 --> 00:17:20.079
whether it's Kidogo--

00:17:20.079 --> 00:17:22.210
a Canadian and an
American who met

00:17:22.210 --> 00:17:26.180
online, moved to Nairobi to
start a nursery, essentially,

00:17:26.180 --> 00:17:30.800
for low income little kids,
and have now turning it

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:34.160
into a franchise and
are really growing.

00:17:34.160 --> 00:17:39.140
Or I just got a note
from an Indonesian named

00:17:39.140 --> 00:17:43.460
[? Irman ?] who took 19
courses, started a company

00:17:43.460 --> 00:17:45.470
to work with smallholders
and really break

00:17:45.470 --> 00:17:47.960
a lot of the barriers
that smallholders

00:17:47.960 --> 00:17:49.820
deal with in Indonesia.

00:17:49.820 --> 00:17:53.390
He's got about 300 employees and
is ready for a series B that--

00:17:53.390 --> 00:18:00.530
We're starting to see this
entrepreneurial imagination

00:18:00.530 --> 00:18:04.160
combined with
dedication translate

00:18:04.160 --> 00:18:06.560
into real change for the world.

00:18:06.560 --> 00:18:10.910
Can you then build a
community of individuals

00:18:10.910 --> 00:18:14.420
who are daring to use the
skills and the attributes

00:18:14.420 --> 00:18:17.270
they have to solve big
problems in the world?

00:18:17.270 --> 00:18:18.840
Because that's what we need.

00:18:18.840 --> 00:18:25.700
We need a movement right now as
we see so much that is cynical,

00:18:25.700 --> 00:18:31.700
lacking trust, because
it lacks trustworthiness,

00:18:31.700 --> 00:18:34.540
a huge divide between
rich and poor,

00:18:34.540 --> 00:18:37.190
the destruction of so
much of our physical

00:18:37.190 --> 00:18:39.980
and human environment.

00:18:39.980 --> 00:18:43.280
We need a counter
movement that says no.

00:18:43.280 --> 00:18:45.740
What this moment
in history offers

00:18:45.740 --> 00:18:48.560
through our interdependence is
an opportunity like humanity

00:18:48.560 --> 00:18:52.770
has never had in history that we
can work across lines to create

00:18:52.770 --> 00:18:56.690
the new kinds of companies,
the new institutions that

00:18:56.690 --> 00:18:59.330
allow us to bring our best
selves to one another.

00:18:59.330 --> 00:19:02.090
And what the
ecosystem that we're

00:19:02.090 --> 00:19:05.780
seeing through the fellows, the
companies that we've invested,

00:19:05.780 --> 00:19:09.480
the online community is
showing is just that.

00:19:09.480 --> 00:19:13.160
That this is a possibility
and it's something

00:19:13.160 --> 00:19:16.250
that we've got to double
down on and really grow.

00:19:16.250 --> 00:19:19.220
This movement for moral
leadership, frankly,

00:19:19.220 --> 00:19:22.820
and a more inclusive
type of capitalism

00:19:22.820 --> 00:19:25.677
that is measured by the
amount of human energy

00:19:25.677 --> 00:19:28.010
we release in the world, the
amount of human flourishing

00:19:28.010 --> 00:19:32.120
and dignity, not just how
much money we make, or even

00:19:32.120 --> 00:19:34.380
how much money we give away.

00:19:34.380 --> 00:19:35.380
PRASAD SETTY: Thank you.

