these different lines that

00:27:50.050 --> 00:27:51.340
keep us separated.

00:27:51.340 --> 00:27:55.720
Religion, class, ethnicity,
ideology, geography.

00:27:55.720 --> 00:27:59.920
And so whether-- we've started
in three regions, Pakistan,

00:27:59.920 --> 00:28:01.760
India, and East Africa.

00:28:01.760 --> 00:28:07.120
And we find amazing
leaders across all sectors,

00:28:07.120 --> 00:28:08.740
and all of these
different lines.

00:28:08.740 --> 00:28:12.910
If you take a country like
India, which is so vast,

00:28:12.910 --> 00:28:15.670
you have some young
Indians that have

00:28:15.670 --> 00:28:17.370
gone to the best
schools in the world

00:28:17.370 --> 00:28:19.030
and have graduated at
the top of their class

00:28:19.030 --> 00:28:20.863
and want to use those
skills to make change.

00:28:20.863 --> 00:28:26.290
Suhani Mohan, number
one at the IIT Mumbai.

00:28:26.290 --> 00:28:29.650
Then you went to
investment banking,

00:28:29.650 --> 00:28:31.230
and after a few
years thought, I'm

00:28:31.230 --> 00:28:33.910
among the most educated
people on the planet,

00:28:33.910 --> 00:28:36.370
and yet I go to the villages
and women have no access

00:28:36.370 --> 00:28:39.280
to even basic health hygiene.

00:28:39.280 --> 00:28:46.260
And so she started a feminine
hygiene company a few years ago

00:28:46.260 --> 00:28:51.070
and just sold her millionth
biodegradable sanitary pad.

00:28:51.070 --> 00:28:55.037
And is using the network
of fellows to do this.

00:28:55.037 --> 00:28:56.620
To do that effectively,
she's actually

00:28:56.620 --> 00:29:00.780
got to understand how people
in far flung villages who

00:29:00.780 --> 00:29:03.280
don't speak her language, who
have a different religion, who

00:29:03.280 --> 00:29:08.300
are in some cases deeply
conservative, how they think,

00:29:08.300 --> 00:29:09.490
how they respond.

00:29:09.490 --> 00:29:12.310
And so our fellows
program includes people

00:29:12.310 --> 00:29:15.550
from those villages, but
who are incredible leaders

00:29:15.550 --> 00:29:16.910
in their own right.

00:29:16.910 --> 00:29:21.970
And we bring them together and
both hold up a mirror to them,

00:29:21.970 --> 00:29:24.130
where do you get
in your own way?

00:29:24.130 --> 00:29:25.370
What is your identity?

00:29:25.370 --> 00:29:26.860
How do you think through it?

00:29:26.860 --> 00:29:29.020
We use literature
as a springboard

00:29:29.020 --> 00:29:37.570
into conversation, using moral
leaders as that springboard.

00:29:37.570 --> 00:29:39.850
Regardless of where they
come from in the world

00:29:39.850 --> 00:29:42.040
they will read the
same curriculum.

00:29:42.040 --> 00:29:46.420
Everyone from Plato and Hobbes
and Rousseau to [? Huldoon, ?]

00:29:46.420 --> 00:29:49.990
one of the great
Islamic mathematicians

00:29:49.990 --> 00:29:51.970
and philosophers.

00:29:51.970 --> 00:29:55.930
They read Haile Selassie,
and Chinua Achebe

00:29:55.930 --> 00:30:00.202
of Nigeria, Gandhi, of course
Mandela, King, Aung San Suu

00:30:00.202 --> 00:30:01.910
Kyi.

00:30:01.910 --> 00:30:06.550
And there's a pantheon
of moral leaders

00:30:06.550 --> 00:30:10.570
who have been engaged in the
same conversation for 2,500

00:30:10.570 --> 00:30:11.620
years.

00:30:11.620 --> 00:30:13.240
What is the nature of man?

00:30:13.240 --> 00:30:15.850
How do we make trade offs
between the individual, which

00:30:15.850 --> 00:30:20.230
we're seeing reigning
supreme in Silicon Valley,

00:30:20.230 --> 00:30:24.940
and the community where many
of the places that we work

00:30:24.940 --> 00:30:26.260
takes precedence?

00:30:26.260 --> 00:30:30.250
How do you trade off
freedom and security

00:30:30.250 --> 00:30:33.130
at this moment where so
many people are afraid?

00:30:33.130 --> 00:30:37.322
How do you trade off
justice, or do you?

00:30:37.322 --> 00:30:39.530
What's the difference between
justice and generosity?

00:30:39.530 --> 00:30:40.330
What's easier?

00:30:40.330 --> 00:30:42.610
We have those kinds
of conversations,

00:30:42.610 --> 00:30:45.280
stepping back, reflecting, so
that you can both understand

00:30:45.280 --> 00:30:48.760
more who you are and what your
values are and the principles

00:30:48.760 --> 00:30:49.660
by which you live.

00:30:49.660 --> 00:30:53.470
Because we live in
a moment in history

00:30:53.470 --> 00:30:57.362
where our leaders are flinging
opinion at one another.

00:30:57.362 --> 00:30:58.820
They are not standing
on principle.

00:30:58.820 --> 00:31:03.010
They are not helping us make
sense of this tumultuous time

00:31:03.010 --> 00:31:04.210
in the world.

00:31:04.210 --> 00:31:06.570
And we can't wait
for them to do so.

00:31:06.570 --> 00:31:11.710
And so by bringing these
uncomfortable groups together

00:31:11.710 --> 00:31:15.580
and moderating these
kinds of conversations,

00:31:15.580 --> 00:31:18.550
not only can they learn more
about themselves and each

00:31:18.550 --> 00:31:22.120
other, but develop the tools
to have difficult conversations

00:31:22.120 --> 00:31:24.670
across lines of difference
and then find their tribe--

00:31:24.670 --> 00:31:26.630
their real tribes--

00:31:26.630 --> 00:31:28.510
in the groups that
are trying to solve

00:31:28.510 --> 00:31:30.070
the problems of education.

00:31:30.070 --> 00:31:32.890
Regardless if they come from
a tribal village of Pakistan,

00:31:32.890 --> 00:31:37.420
or an elite school in
India, or a slum in Nairobi,

00:31:37.420 --> 00:31:40.649
or a university in Rwanda.

00:31:40.649 --> 00:31:42.190
That's a tribe
because they're trying

00:31:42.190 --> 00:31:46.060
to solve a problem together,
or off grid energy,

00:31:46.060 --> 00:31:49.360
or health care for the poor.

00:31:49.360 --> 00:31:53.980
That for me is so
incredibly hopeful.

00:31:53.980 --> 00:31:58.120
And that goes to this idea
that we could create a citizen

00:31:58.120 --> 00:32:00.100
movement that transcends.

00:32:00.100 --> 00:32:03.920
But we can't do it if elites
are only talking to each other.

00:32:03.920 --> 00:32:06.460
We need to bring
people who have never

00:32:06.460 --> 00:32:11.080
been able to sit at the
table to bring those voices.

00:32:11.080 --> 00:32:13.840
We need to stop
seeing them as needy

00:32:13.840 --> 00:32:16.600
and recognize how
needed they are.

00:32:16.600 --> 00:32:19.360
And that requires
this moral revolution.

00:32:19.360 --> 00:32:22.660
We've had the
technological revolution.

00:32:22.660 --> 00:32:25.090
I actually think
there's a yearning

00:32:25.090 --> 00:32:27.367
for a moral revolution.

00:32:27.367 --> 00:32:28.700
We just don't know how to do it.

00:32:28.700 --> 00:32:31.840
And we're not seeing
it in our leaders.

00:32:31.840 --> 00:32:34.610
But we know that we don't
like what we're seeing.

00:32:34.610 --> 00:32:38.890
And so how do we develop
the new frameworks

00:32:38.890 --> 00:32:41.490
within which we can
all find ourselves,

00:32:41.490 --> 00:32:48.520
and how do we find a
minimum set of values

00:32:48.520 --> 00:32:52.939
that we can all sign up
for and we can all share?

00:32:52.939 --> 00:32:54.730
That actually shouldn't
be that hard to do.

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:00.790
We can't approach
each other with fear.

00:33:00.790 --> 00:33:06.610
We have to have the moral
courage to start by listening.

00:33:06.610 --> 00:33:10.420
And we can't start by
trying to convince,

00:33:10.420 --> 00:33:15.410
we have to listen in a way
that's ready to be convinced.

00:33:15.410 --> 00:33:17.460
PRASAD SETTY: Thank you.

00:33:17.460 --> 00:33:21.330
Talking about courage,
one of the things

00:33:21.330 --> 00:33:27.180
that has stood out for me is
how you, as well as Acumen,

00:33:27.180 --> 00:33:28.890
both at an individual
level, but also

00:33:28.890 --> 00:33:31.620
at an organizational
level, constantly keep

00:33:31.620 --> 00:33:33.805
reinventing yourselves as well.

00:33:33.805 --> 00:33:37.140
And think about
what is required,

00:33:37.140 --> 00:33:38.700
what can we learn
from the past, what

00:33:38.700 --> 00:33:41.400
is required with the
environment that we see now?

00:33:41.400 --> 00:33:45.650
So as you think about parting
thoughts for this group

00:33:45.650 --> 00:33:49.970
and anyone who might see us in
the big wide world of YouTube,

00:33:49.970 --> 00:33:53.110
what messages do
you have for us?

00:33:53.110 --> 00:33:57.179
Where are you headed personally,
as well as for Acumen?

00:33:57.179 --> 00:33:59.220
JACQUELINE NOVOGRATZ: Well
you started by saying,

00:33:59.220 --> 00:34:01.553
you know, what are the things
that you're most proud of?

00:34:01.553 --> 00:34:07.710
And as I think back to that
beginning of our conversation,

00:34:07.710 --> 00:34:12.389
we didn't start Acumen to prove
that with impact investing

00:34:12.389 --> 00:34:15.540
you could make money in
low income communities.

00:34:15.540 --> 00:34:18.270
We started Acumen because we
wanted to solve the toughest

00:34:18.270 --> 00:34:20.250
issues of poverty.

00:34:20.250 --> 00:34:23.520
That has become a North
Star for us, a thread.

00:34:23.520 --> 00:34:25.510
That makes courage really easy.

00:34:25.510 --> 00:34:28.590
Nietzsche says that
when you know your why

00:34:28.590 --> 00:34:32.520
you can bear almost any how.

00:34:32.520 --> 00:34:35.929
You can endure it anyhow.

00:34:35.929 --> 00:34:39.570
And so as the world
has changed, we

00:34:39.570 --> 00:34:44.639
have had to change to
stay true to our mission.

00:34:44.639 --> 00:34:48.270
And that's-- on the one
hand it's courageous,

00:34:48.270 --> 00:34:51.989
but on a much larger
hand it's thrilling.

00:34:51.989 --> 00:34:54.810
Because I think that for
too long, and certainly

00:34:54.810 --> 00:34:57.750
in my generation,
we divided the world

00:34:57.750 --> 00:34:59.760
between the do-gooders
and the people

00:34:59.760 --> 00:35:00.930
who wanted to make money.

00:35:00.930 --> 00:35:03.450
That world doesn't
exist anymore.

00:35:03.450 --> 00:35:07.170
One, if we are going to
create the world that we

00:35:07.170 --> 00:35:10.140
are capable of creating,
we have to recognize

00:35:10.140 --> 00:35:11.784
that every single
one of us is needed.

00:35:11.784 --> 00:35:13.200
Whether you work
in a corporation,

00:35:13.200 --> 00:35:14.991
whether you work in
government, whether you

00:35:14.991 --> 00:35:17.970
work for a nonprofit in the
civil society or a community

00:35:17.970 --> 00:35:19.440
organization.

00:35:19.440 --> 00:35:23.700
And we've got to approach each
other from a place of building

00:35:23.700 --> 00:35:27.676
trust, not thinking that I
have the answers and you don't.

00:35:27.676 --> 00:35:29.550
I'm in the corporate
world and I'm efficient,

00:35:29.550 --> 00:35:30.590
and you're in the
nonprofit world

00:35:30.590 --> 00:35:33.450
and you might have a big heart,
but you can't manage yourself

00:35:33.450 --> 00:35:35.190
out of a shoe box.

00:35:35.190 --> 00:35:37.860
Obviously there may be
truth for individuals,

00:35:37.860 --> 00:35:39.830
but there are not truths.

00:35:39.830 --> 00:35:42.600
There's no capital-T
truth to that.

00:35:42.600 --> 00:35:50.070
So one is this idea of be
audacious in the problems

00:35:50.070 --> 00:35:52.570
that we are trying to change.

00:35:52.570 --> 00:35:55.350
But then have the humility
to start where you are.

00:35:55.350 --> 00:35:56.940
Just take a step.

00:35:56.940 --> 00:35:58.740
I worry with the next
generation is there

00:35:58.740 --> 00:36:03.000
such a focus on
perfection sometimes

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:06.300
that people are too
afraid to make a move?

00:36:06.300 --> 00:36:07.740
Just make a move.

00:36:07.740 --> 00:36:11.730
And then once you take a
step, let the work teach you.

00:36:11.730 --> 00:36:14.130
Probably the second
big parting thought

00:36:14.130 --> 00:36:16.380
would be that came
from my mentor

00:36:16.380 --> 00:36:21.210
here in Silicon
Valley, John Gardner.

00:36:21.210 --> 00:36:23.040
In this age of
celebrity we so often

00:36:23.040 --> 00:36:25.195
focus on being interesting.

00:36:25.195 --> 00:36:26.820
The people who make
change in the world

00:36:26.820 --> 00:36:28.800
focus on being interested.

00:36:28.800 --> 00:36:30.600
Find out about others.

00:36:30.600 --> 00:36:34.080
Understand the problem
from their perspective.

00:36:34.080 --> 00:36:36.330
Have the courage to fail,
and then just get up

00:36:36.330 --> 00:36:37.260
and start again.

00:36:37.260 --> 00:36:39.480
It's not the smart
people necessarily

00:36:39.480 --> 00:36:42.360
who make the change, it's
the determined people.

00:36:42.360 --> 00:36:45.570
And then find a
community, find a tribe

00:36:45.570 --> 00:36:47.880
that's willing to stand
with you as you stand

00:36:47.880 --> 00:36:50.460
with the poor and the marginal.

00:36:50.460 --> 00:36:54.730
Because that can be
a lonely journey.

00:36:54.730 --> 00:36:59.910
It will be a lonely
journey at times.

00:36:59.910 --> 00:37:01.860
You got to be able to
find the joy that's

00:37:01.860 --> 00:37:02.980
inside of it as well.

00:37:02.980 --> 00:37:05.180
And that doesn't
happen by yourself.

00:37:05.180 --> 00:37:06.630
That happens with the community.

00:37:06.630 --> 00:37:11.310
And what's been so
wonderful, and joyful,

00:37:11.310 --> 00:37:15.570
and fulfilling about partnering
with Google, and with you,

00:37:15.570 --> 00:37:20.280
and the team that you bring
is that, like you said,

00:37:20.280 --> 00:37:24.210
this is a journey
of kindred spirits

00:37:24.210 --> 00:37:29.610
that are driven by answering
problems, not by being right.

00:37:29.610 --> 00:37:35.160
And if you can take that kind
of attitude for the long term,

00:37:35.160 --> 00:37:37.380
there's not a problem
we can't solve.

00:37:37.380 --> 00:37:40.920
We should be bold enough
to dare to end poverty

00:37:40.920 --> 00:37:42.840
in our lifetimes.

00:37:42.840 --> 00:37:46.090
Not just the material
poverty, but the poverty

00:37:46.090 --> 00:37:48.450
that's keeping us
most apart from one

00:37:48.450 --> 00:37:50.310
another, certainly
in the United States,

00:37:50.310 --> 00:37:55.200
and that is a spiritual sense
of impoverishment, of isolation,

00:37:55.200 --> 00:37:58.380
of not counting,
of being left out.

00:37:58.380 --> 00:38:02.240
And that's the one we
have to work on the most.

00:38:02.240 --> 00:38:05.310
And there is no
way to work on it

00:38:05.310 --> 00:38:12.050
than to pursue lives of
purpose, of meaning, of taking

00:38:12.050 --> 00:38:14.450
on the hardest problems
that we need to solve

00:38:14.450 --> 00:38:16.931
and can only solve together.

00:38:16.931 --> 00:38:17.930
PRASAD SETTY: Thank you.

00:38:17.930 --> 00:38:20.090
Thank you for living
that life of purpose,

00:38:20.090 --> 00:38:22.400
being an inspiration
to so many people

00:38:22.400 --> 00:38:24.470
that are in the
organization, as well as

00:38:24.470 --> 00:38:26.137
your own fellows and enlistees.

00:38:26.137 --> 00:38:27.470
JACQUELINE NOVOGRATZ: Thank you.

00:38:27.470 --> 00:38:29.540
And thank you to Google.

00:38:29.540 --> 00:38:33.390
Truly you've been with us
every step of this journey.

00:38:33.390 --> 00:38:36.500
And I think we're at
a level and a place

00:38:36.500 --> 00:38:39.260
right now to just go
deeper together and learn

00:38:39.260 --> 00:38:40.350
from each other.

00:38:40.350 --> 00:38:41.830
And I look forward to that.

00:38:41.830 --> 00:38:42.520
All right.

00:38:42.520 --> 00:38:43.720
Thank you, Jacqueline.

00:38:43.720 --> 00:38:46.770
[APPLAUSE]

